Title: The Midnight Library
Author: Matt Haig
My Review:
This was a pleasant read, but a little predictable at times.

Nora Seed has had a series of unfortunate events in her life (losing her job, friends drifting apart, cat dying), and decides to take her life. She OD's and ends up in The Midnight Library where she is given a chance to live out other versions of her life by a mystical librarian from her past, the various books representing the alternate realities. It was rather nice to see how she sees herself in various other lives, each of them representing a desire, a "what would have been." However, the one thing that made me roll my eyes a bit is that after noticing something small or large not according to her expectations, she quickly grows weary of the life and heads back to the library, almost as if the chapter is being quickly ended by the author (this is my imagination and is not featured in the novel). Also, the various references to quasi-science of quantum universes felt unnecessary.

The novel redeemed itself in the third act where Nora goes to a seemingly perfect life, and understands how much impact she has had on everyone by the doing (or the lack of doing) of a certain thing, big or small. The protagonist almost becomes incidental to the narration as the author inserts a lot of life lessons, that actually read quite well and don't come across as hackneyed. Finally, Nora ultimately goes back to her life and all is well!

Almost well. Since this is a semi sci-fi novel, I wished the cat would return; just as the only change in her old life, a small gift from the librarian perhaps.

Title: The Reason I Jump: The Inner Voice of a Thirteen-Year-Old Boy with Autism
Author: Naoki Higashida
My Review:
This is a beautiful little book written by a kid with autism. It is in the form of Q&A, an "everything you wanted to know about autism but were too afraid to ask." It provides such a wonderful window into what an autistic/special needs child goes through. Many parts of the book made me quite emotional. He describes his experiences in a very heartfelt manner. He implores the reader to understand that special needs children have the intellect and the desire to learn about the world around them. But they are just unable to react and learn the same way as others, because of how their brain and their senses react to stimuli, experiences and the constant changes around them.

A truly unique book to which I am definitely coming back.

Title: How Not to Die: Discover the Foods Scientifically Proven to Prevent and Reverse Disease
Author: Michael  Greger
My Review:
A highly informative, practical guide to healthy eating and vegetarianism/veganism. He goes into great detail about how various kinds of vegan foods, like whole grains, fruits, vegetables, beverages, and spices help in preventing and/or delaying the 15 major diseases that affect the modern human. He then talks about each food category and also provides an occasional recipe!

Full of health and nutritional facts, Dr Greger gives practical advice on the kind and the quantity of food to eat to prevent disease. All the claims are backed up by strong scientific research cited by the author, and the oft-quoted "randomised, double-blind, placebo controlled trials."

If you're looking for a complete yet easy to read guide on nutrition and health, this is definitely the book for you.

Title: The Silent Patient
Author: Alex Michaelides
My Review:
A great setup and a fun twist at the end but...

The whole of the middle was just OK for me. I was bugged by the many psych novel tropes, and though it set out to be a thriller/horror, it left me mildly surprised at best. Most of the characters were pretty flat, and felt partially developed. I couldn't believe how whole dialogues were written as diary entries, nor how one could write a diary when there is an intruder in the house or under heavy sedation.

Maybe I'm being too harsh though, it's a really good novel for a debut author. Michaelides knows the formula to write a suspenseful page-turner.

Title: Middlesex
Author: Jeffrey Eugenides
My Review: What an epic! Middlesex spans three generations and does justice to all of them. At the center is Cal (Calliope), an intersex person who narrates the lives of her immigrant grandparents, her American parents and her own. The complexities of a family in an ever changing landscape is beautifully brought forth by Eugenides in simple, humorous and moving prose, to which you will remain glued through the course of your reading.

Title: Lolita
Author: Vladimir Nabokov
My Review: How can such a horrifying novel be so well-written? Nabokov writes Humbert's perverse thoughts and actions in beautiful, unforgettable prose without any use of vulgarity. The subject matter made me put the book away many times, but the writing brought my back. The unreliability of the narrator, either because of a possible mental illness or his propensity to exaggerate and twist the truth to his liking makes for a surprising, all-is-not-well ending. I will definitely read this book again.

Title: Bossypants
Author: Tina Fey
My Review: A delightful read, especially for a fan. Every line is funny, made even better by Tina's hilarious delivery in the audiobook version. She details her awkward earlier years as a kid and teenager, and even more awkward later years as a comedian in Second City and a writer/actor in SNL and 30 Rock. A key takeaway from this book is to never be embarrassed about being a geek. Creativity, smart work and a bit of luck make for a successful career and a happy life.

But definitely read it if you're a fan of the first book, or just want to know what the hype was all about.

Title: Fahrenheit 451
Author: Ray Bradbury
My Review: I was too young to appreciate it the first time I read this book. I read it again and it was wonderful. It is more relatable now, and I can picture our society headed that way where mass media and entertainment controls our lives so much that our attention spans are shortened, face to face communication is all but forgotten and we are simply made to believe what we are told. To me, it wasn't even about book burning towards the end, but how one man wants to be more human and less a cog in the system.
